Data Description

The data I choose describes the payment required when visiting a hospital, the type of admission to the hospital, and the severity of the illness. I want to know if the price paid when arriving is dependent on the type of admission and the severity. We will start by first looking at some summary statistics. Lets looks at the two factors individually, and then in combination.

data <- read.csv("test_data.csv")
admission_type_summ <- data %>%
  group_by(Type.of.Admission) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Admission_Deposit), sd = sd(Admission_Deposit), median = median(Admission_Deposit),   IQR = IQR(Admission_Deposit), mode = getmode(Admission_Deposit), sampeSize = length(Admission_Deposit))
severity_type_summ <- data %>%
  group_by(Severity.of.Illness) %>%

admission_severity_summ <- data %>%
  group_by(Type.of.Admission, Severity.of.Illness) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Admission_Deposit), sd = sd(Admission_Deposit), median = median(Admission_Deposit),   IQR = IQR(Admission_Deposit), mode = getmode(Admission_Deposit), sampeSize = length(Admission_Deposit))
#Some data cleaning to make it easier to work with

Tests

One-way ANOVA

Now I will perform a one-way ANOVA test on both the severity of illness and the type of admission. This will tell us if the means of each level of severity and admission type are the same with respect to there individual groups.

model1 <- aov(data$Admission_Deposit ~ data$Severity.of.Illness, data=data)
anova1 <- anova(model1)

rownames(anova1) <- c("Severity of Illness", "Error")
knitr::kable(anova1)
Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
Severity of Illness 2 779121206 389560603 335.1379 0
Error 137054 159310059030 1162389 NA NA

Hypotheses

\(H_0: \ \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3\)

\(H_1:\) at least one is different

Test Statistic

\(F_{0} = 335.138\)

p-value

\(p < 0.0001\)

Rejection Region

Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that at least one of the average admission deposits is different based on severity of illness.

model2 <- aov(data$Admission_Deposit ~ data$Type.of.Admission, data=data)
anova2 <- anova(model2)
rownames(anova2) <- c("Type of Admission", "Error")

Post Hoc Testing

We know from the ANOVA results that the means of admission deposit are not the same for both severity of illness and the type of admission. Now all of the pairwise contrasts will be looked at using Tukeys test.

tukey <- TukeyHSD(x=model1, 'data$Severity.of.Illness', conf.level=0.95)
tky <- as.data.frame(tukey$`data$Severity.of.Illness`)
tky$`data$Severity.of.Illness` <- rownames(tky)
Comparison p-value Significant?
Minor vs.Extreme 0.0000 Yes
Moderate vs.Extreme 0.0000 Yes
Moderate vs.Minor 0.0000 Yes 
ggplot(tky) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(tky$`data$Severity.of.Illness`, ymin=tky$lwr, ymax=tky$upr), width=0.2) +
  geom_point(aes(tky$`data$Severity.of.Illness`, tky$diff)) + 
  theme_ipsum() + ylab("Difference in mean levels") + xlab("") + 
  geom_hline(yintercept=0, lty="11", colour="grey30") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

tukey <- TukeyHSD(x=model2, 'data$Type.of.Admission', conf.level=0.95)
tky <- as.data.frame(tukey$`data$Type.of.Admission`)
tky$`data$Type.of.Admission` <- rownames(tky)
Comparison p-value Significant?
Trauma vs.Emergency 0.0000 Yes
Urgent vs.Emergency 0.0000 Yes
Urgent vs.Trauma 0.0000 Yes 
ggplot(tky) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(tky$`data$Type.of.Admission`, ymin=tky$lwr, ymax=tky$upr), width=0.2) +
  geom_point(aes(tky$`data$Type.of.Admission`, tky$diff)) + 
  theme_ipsum() + ylab("Difference in mean levels") + xlab("") + 
  geom_hline(yintercept=0, lty="11", colour="grey30") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

These plots tell us that the means can not be assumed equal for any combination of two groups, with respect to the parent group the belong to (severity or admission type). This is a visual representation of checking if \(p < .05\). If the vertical lines do not cover the horizontal line, which is zero for these plots, then that interaction is significant. Something to note, the p-values for all of the interactions from both groups was so small that it returned zero.

One-way ANOVA Assumptions

Now lets verify the ANOVA assumptions. I want to see if the residuals (errors) model a normal distribution with a mean of zero and a constant variance.

res1 <- resid(model1)
res2 <- resid(model2)

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=res1, group=Severity.of.Illness, fill=Severity.of.Illness)) +
    geom_density(alpha=.3) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Residual') + 
    ylab('Density') + labs(fill = 'Severity of Illness') +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Paired")

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=res2, group=Type.of.Admission, fill=Type.of.Admission)) +
    geom_density(alpha=.3) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Residual') + 
    ylab('Density') + labs(fill = 'Type of Admission') +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set1")

The above density plots of the residuals model a normal distribution and have a mean that I will call close enough to zero.

ggplot(data=data, aes(y=res1, x=Severity.of.Illness, fill=Severity.of.Illness)) +
    geom_point(alpha=.5) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Severity of Illness') + 
    ylab('Redisual') + theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot(data=data, aes(y=res2, x=Type.of.Admission, fill=Type.of.Admission)) +
    geom_point(alpha=.5) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Type of Admission') + 
    ylab('Redisual') + theme(legend.position = "none")

These two plots are used to look at the variance. We say that the variance across the subgroups should be constant. These plots imply that is true. This is because the vertical lines are about the same length.

Two-way ANOVA

Hypotheses

\(H_0:\) There is not an interaction between severity of illness and type of admission

\(H_1:\) There is an interaction between severity of illness and type of admission

model3 <- aov(data$Admission_Deposit ~ data$Severity.of.Illness * data$Type.of.Admission, data=data)
anova_two <- anova(model3)

rownames(anova_two) <- c("Severity of Illness", "Type of Admission", "Severity and Admission Type", "Error")
knitr::kable(anova_two)
Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
Severity of Illness 2 779121206 389560603 338.19497 0.000000
Type of Admission 2 1425631148 712815574 618.82706 0.000000
Severity and Admission Type 4 21342848 5335712 4.63217 0.000973
Error 137048 157863085034 1151882 NA NA

Test Statistic

\(F_{0} = 4.632\)

p-value

\(p = 0.001\)

Rejection Region

Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that there is an interaction between severity of illness and type of admission.

prof_data <- data %>%
  group_by(Severity.of.Illness, Type.of.Admission) %>%
  summarise_at(vars(Admission_Deposit), funs(mean(., na.rm=TRUE)))

ggplot(data=prof_data, aes(x = prof_data$Severity.of.Illness, y = prof_data$Admission_Deposit,              group=prof_data$Type.of.Admission, color=prof_data$Type.of.Admission)) +
    geom_line() +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Severity') + 
    ylab('Average Admission Deposit') + labs(color = 'Type of Admission') + 
    ggtitle('Profile Plot')

The profile plot does not show the interaction the two-way ANOVA test found. This is because of the size of the dataset. When there is this much data a small interaction can cause the ANOVA test to be rejected. However, the interaction might not be significant enough to matter or even show up in the profile plot. Due to the plot showing the interaction is not significant, I will now look at ANOVA without the interaction.

model4 <- aov(data$Admission_Deposit ~ data$Severity.of.Illness+data$Type.of.Admission, data = data)
anova_two_no <- anova(model4)
rownames(anova_two_no) <- c("Severity of Illness", "Type of Admission", "Error")
knitr::kable(anova_two_no)

Two-way ANOVA Without Interactions

Test Statistic

p-value

\(p < 0.0001\)

Rejection Region

Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that there is a main effect of severity of illness.

Hypotheses

Two-way ANOVA Assumptions

almost_sas(model3)

Much like the one-way assumptions we want to look for a normal distribution of residuals with a mean of zero and constant variance. The upper left plot verifies that the variance is constant across all residuals. The other three plots verify the normality of the residuals. The density and histogram plot show the shape of a normal distribution with a mean around zero.
